subject: Add callback for response handling to HttpClient
commitMessage:
Add callback for response handling to HttpClient

Adds sendDataWithCallback() which allows the caller to include a
callback specifying how to handle the response to that
request.  This will be utilized for Redfish Aggregation
including returning the responses received when forwarding
requests to satellite BMCs.

Change-Id: I93826c8b254a5f28a982295d4145453352a90fae
Signed-off-by: Carson Labrado <clabrado@google.com>

Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as 039a47e3474d5667d295984f330e876aef309eac
Looking really good here.
Similar to how we handle this in the server connection class, should this just be a member variable rather than constructing it from stack?  That seems like it would make more optimal use of memory.
That shouldn't cause any issues.  I've made the change.
This is making a complete copy of the response object, I suspect you want release() instead of get() here.
I made the swap to release()
This isn't the right check.  Per http, you need to be checking the content-type header to determine if this is intended to be parsed as json or not.

Actually, is there a reason to parse the body as a json here?  I thought it was needed for AsyncResp to actually generate the response when destroyed.  However, it looks like jsonValue is only used in generating the actual response when Asyncresp's res.body() is empty and needs to be constructed from res.jsonValue.

I know in the future I'll want to parse certain responses as jsons. In Redfish Aggregation I'll need to do that in order to fixup links in responses from satellite BMCs, but that's not currently needed by EventService.  Is it alright to leave this for a later patch?

> Actually, is there a reason to parse the body as a json here?

Not really IMO.


>  I thought it was needed for AsyncResp to actually generate the response when destroyed.  However, it looks like jsonValue is only used in generating the actual response when Asyncresp's res.body() is empty and needs to be constructed from res.jsonValue.

Yep, I think you have that right.

> 
> I know in the future I'll want to parse certain responses as jsons. In Redfish Aggregation I'll need to do that in order to fixup links in responses from satellite BMCs, but that's not currently needed by EventService.  Is it alright to leave this for a later patch?

The actual parsing, sure.
Sounds good, I have removed this json parsing and will leave it to a future patch.

This function is called out by name as throwing an exception, and you haven't handled exceptions or errors here;  You need to set argument 3 to false, then check the resulting value against is_discarded();  If the json fails to parse, you need to return an error code to the user.

My bad on missing that.  I will handle this properly, but as noted in an earlier comment I am would like to push potential json parsing of received responses to a later patch.  That parsing would only need to occur for Redfish Aggregation specific processes like link fixup rather than being performed on for all received responses.  I think in that case it would be more appropriate to move it within the callback function that would be provided by the Aggregator.

> My bad on missing that.  I will handle this properly, but as noted in an earlier comment I am would like to push potential json parsing of received responses to a later patch.

Fine by me, and as a pattern (Splitting up patches into sections of features) is a good thing to do.

>  That parsing would only need to occur for Redfish Aggregation specific processes like link fixup rather than being performed on for all received responses.  I think in that case it would be more appropriate to move it within the callback function that would be provided by the Aggregator.



Sounds good.
I've removed the parsing from this patch

I see what you're trying to do here, but I struggle with this, because when you do this, there's no way to differentiate between "The other server returned 500" and "http client ran out of retries".

I suspect we should be returning something like 502, bad gateway here?

That's a fair point, I'm good with returning 502 here.  I didn't see an internalError() equivalent for a 502 so I just directly set res.result as bad_gateway.  Is that alright or is there a preferred method I should use?

On a related note, I suspect that later we'll want to directly return certain non-200 codes from the other server rather than retrying until we hit the max number of retries and return a 502.  I do this for 404 in a later patch and I'm sure there will be others come up as Redfish Aggregation is implemented.

> That's a fair point, I'm good with returning 502 here.  I didn't see an internalError() equivalent for a 502 so I just directly set res.result as bad_gateway.  Is that alright or is there a preferred method I should use?

The one that looks right to me is OperationFailed.  The description for it is:

"Indicates that one of the internal operations necessary to complete the request failed.  Examples of this are when an internal service provider is unable to complete the request, such as in aggregation or RDE."

Which sounds like exactly what we're trying to do here.

> 
> On a related note, I suspect that later we'll want to directly return certain non-200 codes from the other server rather than retrying until we hit the max number of retries and return a 502.  I do this for 404 in a later patch and I'm sure there will be others come up as Redfish Aggregation is implemented.


Agreed, we'll want to eventually forward errors from the aggregated instance, that's why my original comment is important, so we can differentiate between "The server we were talking to returned 500" and "the server we're talking to timed out"

> The one that looks right to me is OperationFailed

I couldn't just call redfish::messages::operationFailed() since that would also set the error code as a 500, and overwriting the 500 with 502 seemed redundant.  I also couldn't individually set the result and message here because addMessageToErrorJson() is static.

Instead I added a new function to "redfish-core/include/error_messages.hpp" and "redfish-core/src/error_messages.cpp" which combines the 502 result with the OperationFailed message.

> > The one that looks right to me is OperationFailed
> 
> I couldn't just call redfish::messages::operationFailed() since that would also set the error code as a 500, and overwriting the 500 with 502 seemed redundant.  I also couldn't individually set the result and message here because addMessageToErrorJson() is static.

We should change the code to return 502.  500 is "wrong".  There is literally only once use, in processor.hpp, and that use of it is arguably incorrect.  Lets just change it.

> 
> Instead I added a new function to "redfish-core/include/error_messages.hpp" and "redfish-core/src/error_messages.cpp" which combines the 502 result with the OperationFailed message.

I have a patch fixing that here: https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/53758

Just use the existing OperationFailed, and once that patch merges, the code will be correct.
nit, please make the callback const.  we don't expect the user to be modifying response after this point.

I changed it so that "Response&" is now "const Response&" in all callback instances.  I also had to add const to Response.resultInt() so that it could still be called in the dummy callback's debug message.

I'm reopening this due to removing the parsing from recvMessage().

In the callback the user might want to use std::move() to load res.stringResponse into an AsyncResp object or nlohmann::json::parse() to create a json.  Neither of those are usable with a "const Response".  Can I remove const to enable those operations or will that callback need to create a duplicate copy that can then be operated on?
OOOO, good point.  Fine as is.
nit, can this just be a static method instead of a lambda?  MIght make this easier to read.
No problem
